Day 4: Mastering Editing Basics for Photo and Video - No Pro Skills Required! 

Start with these basics ⬇️

 🖼 Photo Editing (Lightroom Mobile or Snapseed)
- Enhance brightness + contrast
- Color correction basics
- Remove minor flaws
- Sharpen or add clarity to make products stand out

 🎥 Video Editing (CapCut or VN Video Editor)
- Seamless clip stitching
- Dynamic scene switching
- Add text hooks
- Always caption for accessibility!

 ✨ Pro Tip: Simplicity is key. Clean edits win over elaborate transitions.

Day 3: Affordable Backgrounds & Props That Work

You don’t need a studio setup to make your videos look clean and aesthetic.
One of the easiest tricks? Chart papers 🎨
Available in so many colors, they work great as flat lay or backdrop options.

Here’s what you can use: 🩶 Chart papers – solid backgrounds, matte finish = no weird light reflection
🕯️ Minimal props – scrunchies, jars, trays, fabric, candles
📚 Books or wooden boards – great for layering
🌿 Plants or flowers – add a soft, lifestyle vibe

✨ Keep it simple. A clean, intentional frame is more than enough to stand out.

☀️ Lip balm but make it SPF 30.
Tried the Hyphen Lipscreen and here’s my honest take 👇
✔️ Lightweight, non-sticky
✔️ Hydrating + fragrance-free
✔️ SPF 30 = good for daily use
✖️ No tint or gloss (strictly skincare)
✖️ Pricey for 5g — but worth it if you care about lip sun protection

Not your average balm — more like SPF for your lips. 🧴💋
#HyphenLipscreen #SPFForLips #SkincareReview #LipCare

Day 2: Gather Your Basic Tools
.
You don’t need fancy equipment to start UGC.
A good smartphone camera, natural light from a window, and something to keep your phone steady (like a tripod or even a stack of books) are more than enough.

💡 Tip: Natural sunlight is your best friend — shoot near a window during the day for the best results.

Don’t overthink it — many creators start with just these basics and grow from there. The goal is to start, not to be perfect.

Day 1 of UGC journey: Learning the basics
Before you start creating videos or reaching out to brands, it’s super important to understand the key terms and the types of content brands look for.

Here’s what to learn today:
Terms to Google:

Usage rights

Perpetuity (forever usage)

Net 30 (when you get paid)

Brief (brand instructions)

Exclusivity (working with just one brand in a category)

Organic vs paid content

Raw footage

Whitelisting (brand using your content in ads)

Types of content to Google:

Unboxing video

Testimonial video

How-to video

Lifestyle photo

Selfie with product

Problem/solution video

Product comparison

Listicle video (like “Top 3 lip balms”)

Learning this will help you sound more professional and confident when talking to brands!

Comment “Day 1 done!” if you're learning with me, and save this post so you can come back anytime.
